<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-09-27T05:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-09-27T05:00:00-05:00" n="618" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d618">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/10274: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Grew</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-09-27T19:00:00+09:00">September 27, 1937—7
                                        p.m.</date><lb/>[Received September 27—9:01 a.m.]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>423. Our 421, September 27, 5 p.m. As indicative of one of the
                                considerations entering into the decision to cease bombing of
                                Nanking, we are informed by an entirely reliable Japanese source
                                that the Foreign Office has been “deluged” with telegrams from
                                Japanese diplomatic missions in various parts of the world,
                                including the United States, reporting on movements to boycott
                                Japanese goods.</p>
                            <p>Repeated to Shanghai.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Grew</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>